      "fileSummary": "This document outlines a research proposal for the development of **UMSEL (Universal Multimodal Scientific Entity Linking)**, a system designed to standardize entity linking across diverse scientific disciplines.\n\n### 1. Main Objective\nThe project aims to move away from domain-specific entity linking systems, which currently struggle with interdisciplinary research, toward a single, unified model capable of performing accurate entity linking across major scientific databases such as PubMed and arXiv.\n\n### 2. Proposed Methodology\nThe researchers propose a multimodal, transformer-based architecture:\n*   **Input Data:** The model will process an entity mention along with its 512-token surrounding textual context and associated visual elements (e.g., diagrams, plots).\n*   **Data Scale:** The training set will consist of 5 million open-access scientific papers.\n*   **Vision Component:** A generic CNN-based encoder will be utilized to extract structural features from scientific diagrams and figures to assist in the linking process.\n\n### 3. Evaluation Plan\n*   **Datasets:** Performance will be benchmarked against existing public entity linking datasets, specifically:\n    *   BC5CDR\n    *   MedMentions\n    *   SciERC\n*   **Metrics:** The primary metric for success is defined as **Top-1 linking accuracy**.\n*   **Hypothesis:** The authors hypothesize that cross-domain pre-training will outperform current domain-specific baselines.\n\n### 4. Discussion and Future Outlook\n*   **Strength:** The system’s primary value proposition lies in its \"universal\" design, which addresses the limitations of narrow, field-specific tools.\n*   **Future Scope:** Once the core system is established, the researchers plan to extend the model’s utility to include real-time entity linking capabilities for pre-print servers.",
